{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_013y7RpyvqQxTpAQnfDWsnaB","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"No learnings yet - this is the first lane. The repo is empty (just has spec/ and .forge/). \n\nNow I need to bootstrap the project. This is lane 1, the first lane, so I need to:\n1. Scaffold pnpm monorepo with Next.js 15 (App Router), TypeScript, Tailwind v4, Hono API routes, Vitest, Playwright\n2. Docker Compose dev config: PostgreSQL 16, Redis, MinIO, Ollama (optional), app service with hot-reload  \n3. Drizzle ORM setup + initial migration for all models\n\n\n4. Better Auth integration\n\nI'm clarifying the architecture — it's a single Next.js 15 app with Hono integrated into the API routes rather than a traditional monorepo with separate packages, so the Hono routes will live at `/api/*` within the Next.js structure.\n\nFor the directory layout, I'm deciding between keeping everything in a single `src/` folder or using an `apps/web` structure with a shared `packages/db` for the Drizzle schema, but leaning toward the simpler co-located approach to avoid unnecessary complexity. I'm realizing that for a co-located frontend and backend in Next.js, I don't actually need separate apps—the entire project can live in one Next.js app within the monorepo, with just a shared database package for the Drizzle schema and migrations.\n\nNow I'm mapping out the implementation phases: first I'll bootstrap a Next.js 15 app with TypeScript, Tailwind v4, and ESLint, then add the backend dependencies like Hono, Drizzle, Better Auth, and testing tools. After that I'll set up the directory structure and start writing tests for the first feature.\n\nFor the tests themselves, I'm focusing on what makes sense for infrastructure—unit and integration tests that don't require a running database. I'll verify the Vitest config works, validate the Docker Compose setup, test the Drizzle schema and migrations, and ensure Better Auth is properly configured and mounted.\n\nNow I'm mapping out the project structure with the Next.js app directory, server-side code organized by domain, database schema files, and the Hono API layer. Looking at the root-level configuration files and realizing I should leverage Context7 MCP tools for any library setup or codegen work, but I'm not seeing those tools available in my current toolset.\n\nSince I'm working with standard tools, I'll move forward with my existing knowledge and start planning out the test structure for each checkpoint—setting up unit tests for the scaffold validation, database schema definitions, and authentication setup.\n\nWriting test files...\n\nFor the Docker Compose validation, I need to ensure the YAML is properly formatted and includes all the required services. Then I'll tackle the implementation in order: tests first to establish the requirements, followed by configuration files, the database schema, auth setup, API layer, and finally Docker orchestration before running the full test suite.\n\nI'm checking whether I have access to Context7 MCP tools for code generation, but since they're not in my available tools, I'll proceed with my existing knowledge of current library versions. Rather than delegating this to another agent, I should handle the implementation myself using the Forge pattern—starting with the test definitions and working through each component systematically. I need to check what versions of pnpm and Node are available before I start setting up the monorepo structure.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":"tool_use","stop_sequence":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":0,"cache_read_input_tokens":50363,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":0},"output_tokens":2922,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"bb97f10c-f3e9-4d4d-8c90-eca16b368ef0","uuid":"8498de2c-8d51-40c5-a020