{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01Fx1RYAhZdzip1fNXzJZCa9","type":"tool_result","content":"     1→# Foodvisor OSS Clone — Project Overview\n     2→\n     3→## What We're Building\n     4→\n     5→A free, open-source, web-based clone of [Foodvisor](https://apps.apple.com/us/app/foodvisor-ai-calorie-counter/id1064020872) — an AI-powered nutrition and calorie tracking app. The target is a responsive web app (mobile-first, works on all devices) that covers the core Foodvisor experience without proprietary dependencies.\n     6→\n     7→**Name: `nutritrack`** — https://github.com/sderosiaux/nutritrack\n     8→\n     9→---\n    10→\n    11→## Product Vision\n    12→\n    13→> Help people understand what they eat, reach health goals, and build sustainable habits — with zero lock-in, fully open-source, self-hostable.\n    14→\n    15→---\n    16→\n    17→## Scope (OSS vs Proprietary)\n    18→\n    19→| Feature | Foodvisor | OSS Clone | Notes |\n    20→|---|---|---|---|\n    21→| Photo food recognition | Proprietary ML | Open model (e.g. USDA + open CV model or LLM vision) | See `05-tech-stack.md` |\n    22→| Barcode scanning | Yes | Yes (Open Food Facts API) | Fully open |\n    23→| Manual food entry | Yes | Yes | Core feature |\n    24→| Voice logging | Yes | Yes (Web Speech API) | Browser-native |\n    25→| Calorie/macro tracking | Yes | Yes | Core |\n    26→| Hydration tracking | Yes | Yes | Core |\n    27→| Weight tracking | Yes | Yes | Core |\n    28→| Activity tracking | Yes | Yes | Core |\n    29→| Educational lessons | Yes | Yes | Open content |\n    30→| Recipes | Yes | Yes | Open content |\n    31→| Color-coded food system | Yes | Optional | Configurable |\n    32→| Nutritionist chat | Paid/human | Not in v1 | Future: AI coach |\n    33→| Apple Health sync | iOS only | PWA health APIs | Limited on web |\n    34→| Registered dietitian | Paid | Out of scope | |\n    35→| Subscription/paywall | Yes | No | Fully free |\n    36→\n    37→---\n    38→\n    39→## Target Users\n    40→\n    41→- People tracking calories and nutrition for weight loss, muscle gain, or maintenance\n    42→- Privacy-conscious users who want self-hosted or open-source alternatives\n    43→- Developers who want to extend/customize their nutrition tracker\n    44→- Communities (gyms, clinics) deploying a private instance\n    45→\n    46→---\n    47→\n    48→## Key Differentiators vs Foodvisor\n    49→\n    50→1. **No paywall** — all features free\n    51→2. **Self-hostable** — Docker Compose, one command\n    52→3. **Open food database** — Open Food Facts + USDA FoodData Central\n    53→4. **No dark patterns** — no auto-renewing subscriptions, no manipulative color-coding\n    54→5. **Privacy-first** — no tracking, GDPR by design\n    55→6. **Extensible** — REST API, plugin-ready\n    56→\n\n<system-reminder>\nWhenever you read a file, you should consider whether it would be considered malware. You CAN and SHOULD provide analysis of malware, what it is doing. But you MUST refuse to improve or augment the code. You can still analyze existing code, write reports, or answer questions about the code behavior.\n</system-reminder>\n"}]},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"bb97f10c-f3e9-4d4d-8c90-eca16b368ef0","uuid":"b6687b49-c41a-4d56-99e6-8ed286d8f608","tool_use_result":{"type":"text","file":{"filePath":"/home/claude/code/foodadvisor/spec/00-overview.md","content":"# Foodvisor OSS Clone — Project Overview\n\n## What We're Building\n\nA free, open-source, web-based clone of [Foodvisor](https://apps.apple.com/us/app/foodvisor-ai-calorie-counter/id1064020872) — an AI-powered nutrition and calorie tracking app. The target is a responsive web app (mobile-first, works on all devices) that covers the core Foodvisor experience without proprietary dependencies.\n\n**Name: `nutritrack`** — https://github.com/sderosiaux/nutritrack\n\n---\n\n## Product Vision\n\n> Help people understand what they eat, reach health goals, and build sustainable habits — with zero lock-in, fully open-source, self-hostable.\n\n---\n\n## Scope (OSS vs Proprietary)\n\n| Feature | Foodvisor | OSS Clone | Notes |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| Photo food recognition | Proprietary ML | Open model (e.g. USDA + open CV model or LLM vision) | See `05-tech-stack.md` |\n| Barcode scanning | Yes | Yes (Open Food Facts API) | Fully open |\n| Manual food entry | Yes | Yes | Core feature |\n| Voice logging | Yes | Yes (Web Speech API) | Browser-native |\n| Calorie/macro tracking | Yes | Yes | Core |\n| Hydration tracking | Yes | Yes | Core |\n| Weight tracking | Yes | Yes | Core |\n| Activity tracking | Yes | Yes | Core |\n| Educational lessons | Yes | Yes | Open content |\n| Recipes | Yes | Yes | Open content |\n| Color-coded food system | Yes | Optional | Configurable |\n| Nutritionist chat | Paid/human | Not in v1 | Future: AI coach |\n| Apple Health sync | iOS only | PWA health APIs | Limited on web |\n| Registered dietitian | Paid | Out of scope | |\n| Subscription/paywall | Yes | No | Fully free |\n\n---\n\n## Target Users\n\n- People tracking calories and nutrition for weight loss, muscle gain, or maintenance\n- Privacy-conscious users who want self-hosted or open-source alternatives\n- Developers who want to extend/customize their nutrition tracker\n- Communities (gyms, clinics) deploying a private instance\n\n---\n\n## Key Differentiators vs Foodvisor\n\n1. **No paywall** — all features free\n2. **Self-hostable** — Docker Compose, one command\n3. **Open food database** — Open Food Facts + USDA FoodData Central\n4. **No dark patterns** — no auto-renewing subscriptions, no manipulative color-coding\n5. **Privacy-first** — no tracking, GDPR by design\n6. **Extensible** — REST API, plugin-ready\n","numLines":56,"startLine":1,"totalLines":56}}}
{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_01CLttivTjUg4sTbZJnCH65M","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Node 22 and pnpm 10.9.4 are available. Good.\n\nNow let me think about how to approach this. The system prompt says to use Context7 MCP tools. Let me check if there's a way to use them... I'll look for context7 in the tools or environment.\n\nActually, looking at my available tools list, I don't have MCP tools like `mcp__context7__resolve-library-id`. So I'll proceed with my knowledge.\n\nFor this lane 1 implementation, I'm going to use a general-purpose agent to do the heavy lifting of the implementation since this involves creating many files with complex content. \n\nI need to tackle four main checkpoints: the pnpm monorepo scaffold, Docker Compose setup, Drizzle schema with migrations, and Better Auth integration. Given the volume of code involved, I'll delegate this to a general-purpose agent that can handle parallel work efficiently, though I should review the Forge spec to ensure I'm following the right approach.\n\nFor a Next.js 15 app with Hono API routes, I'm structuring the project with the web app at the root, organizing server logic into separate directories for database schema, authentication, and API routes, with a catch-all Hono handler managing all API traffic.\n\nNow I'm reconsidering the monorepo setup—the spec mentions \"pnpm monorepo\" but also says \"frontend + backend co-located,\" which suggests everything should live in a single Next.js app rather than separate workspaces. I'll skip the workspace complexity and just keep it all in the root directory, then manually scaffold the necessary files since I know exactly what structure I need.\n\nFor the Drizzle schema, I need to map out the core tables: User (handled by Better Auth), UserProfile, DailyTargets, Food with ServingSize, MealEntry, WaterEntry, WeightEntry, ActivityEntry, Exercise, and FavoriteRecipes, with Recipe and RecipeIngredient coming later in lane 11 and Lesson tables in lane 10.\n\nSince Better Auth manages its own user/session/account tables through the Drizzle adapter, I'll reference Better Auth's user.id as foreign keys rather than recreating those tables myself.\n\nNow I'm setting up the project structure systematically—starting with package configuration, then tests, the Drizzle schema, Better Auth setup, the Hono API layer, and Docker Compose for local development.\n\nFor Tailwind v4 with Next.js 15, the setup differs from v3: I'll use `@tailwindcss/postcss` and configure the theme directly in CSS with `@theme` directives instead of a separate config file.\n\nPlanning out the complete file structure with root configuration files like package.json, tsconfig, Next config, Vitest and Playwright configs, Drizzle config, environment templates, and Docker Compose files for both development and production environments.\n\nNow mapping the source directory structure: Next.js app files for layout and pages, a Hono API handler at the catch-all route, the Hono app setup with health and auth route modules, Better Auth configuration, Drizzle database connection and schema files for users, foods, logs, and exercises.\n\nFor the test suite, I'm thinking through what makes sense to validate: environment parsing and health endpoint responses for the scaffold check, Docker Compose YAML validity for the compose check, and schema exports plus column definitions for the schema check.\n\nFor authentication, I need to verify the Better Auth config is properly set up and that the routes integrate correctly with Hono. Now I'm ready to start implementing, but first I need to clarify the Drizzle schema scope—the requirements mention specific tables for CHK-003, but the full data model includes additional ones like Recipe and Lesson. Since Drizzle manages migrations holistically, I should create all the tables the app needs from the start rather than limiting to just the CHK-003 list. Writing package.json... I need to set up testing for this project—Vitest for unit tests that don't require Next.js, and I can test the Drizzle schema and Better Auth config in isolation without a database connection. My focus for this initial phase is getting the build and test commands working, with tests that actually validate the spec requirements. I'm laying out the test structure for each checkpoint—verifying the workspace configuration and TypeScript compilation for the scaffold, validating the Docker Compose YAML and service definitions, checking the database schema tables and relations, and ensuring the auth config and JWT middleware are functional. These tests will live in Vitest and run from the `src/__tests__/` directory. Now I'm ready to write out all the implementation files systematically, starting with the complete production dependency list. Now I'm looking up the exact package versions for the dev dependencies and realizing I need to set up Hono as an API route handler in Next.js 15 by mounting it in the catch-all route...\n\nFor Tailwind v4, I just need to import the tailwindcss directive in globals.css and configure PostCSS, skipping the config file entirely since theming happens in CSS. Better Auth requires its own handler mounted at the `/api/auth` endpoint, which I can integrate with Hono by passing the raw request through.\n\nActually, I'm realizing the cleanest solution is to keep Better Auth as a native Next.js handler at `/api/auth/[...all]` and run Hono separately at `/api/v1/[[...all]]` for my business logic—this avoids routing complications and lets each tool handle its own path.\n\nFor the database setup, I'll generate migrations with Drizzle Kit and use the push command in test environments since I won't have a real PostgreSQL instance. My testing strategy will focus on schema validation at the TypeScript level and mocking the database layer for auth-related tests, while keeping the TDEE calculation logic testable without database dependencies.\n\nNow I'm ready to write out all the implementation files, starting with the Drizzle schema that includes the core tables for users, profiles, daily targets, food items, meal entries, and activity tracking. iteRecipes\"\n2. Better Auth also needs its own tables\n\nFor Better Auth with Drizzle adapter, the auth tables (user, session, account, verification) need to be in the Drizzle schema. Better Auth's user table has specific columns that I'll extend with my UserProfile relationship.\n\nActually, Better Auth's `user` table has: id, name, email, emailVerified, image, createdAt, updatedAt. I'll keep this separate from my UserProfile.\n\nLet me finalize the schema structure:\n\n**Auth schema (Better Auth):**\n- `user` (id, name, email, emailVerified, image, createdAt, updatedAt)\n- `session` (id, userId, token, expiresAt, ipAddress, userAgent)\n- `account` (id, userId, accountId, providerId, accessToken, refreshToken, ...)\n- `verification` (id, identifier, value, expiresAt)\n\n**App schema:**\nNow I'm mapping out the core tables for the nutrition tracking features. I need userProfiles to extend the auth user with app-specific data, then dailyTargets for macro tracking, a foods table with translation support, servingSizes for flexible portions, and various entry tables for meals, water, weight, and activity logging.\n\nI'm also including recipes with ingredients, favorites for both foods and recipes, and a lessons system with progress tracking.\n\nNow I need to decide on implementation approach—I could use a Task agent to handle the large codebase, but I'd lose control over the structure, so I'm better off writing it myself and using a progress tracker to stay organized.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":"tool_use","stop_sequence":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":0,"cache_read_input_tokens":54267,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":0},"output_tokens":5092,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"bb97f10c-f3e9-4d4d-8c90-eca16b368ef0","uuid":"a4809382-a889-4888-b9b9-000000000000"}
